1

00:00:02,480  -->  00:00:07,220
Each time you add these higher order or interaction terms to the model,

2

00:00:07,220  -->  00:00:10,500
you should be sure to add each of the lower order terms as well.

3

00:00:10,500  -->  00:00:14,720
We saw how you might be able to identify a quadratic like relationship,

4

00:00:14,720  -->  00:00:17,640
and even higher order terms might be useful when we see

5

00:00:17,640  -->  00:00:21,880
many curves in the relationship between the response and explanatory variables.

6

00:00:21,880  -->  00:00:24,760
But how do you know if you should add an interaction term?

7

00:00:24,760  -->  00:00:28,380
Why would we add something that looks like this into our model?

8

00:00:28,380  -->  00:00:31,720
Let's consider a small example to illustrate this idea.

9

00:00:31,720  -->  00:00:33,700
When adding interaction terms,

10

00:00:33,700  -->  00:00:37,080
you're considering if the way that a variable x1 is related to

11

00:00:37,080  -->  00:00:41,070
your response y is dependent on another variable x2.

12

00:00:41,070  -->  00:00:44,300
As an example, consider that for neighborhood A,

13

00:00:44,300  -->  00:00:49,440
the relationship between the square footage of a house and its price looks like this.

14

00:00:49,440  -->  00:00:51,080
And for neighborhood B,

15

00:00:51,080  -->  00:00:55,460
the relationship between the square footage of a house and the price looks like this.

16

00:00:55,460  -->  00:00:58,600
Here, you can see that the slopes of the lines that

17

00:00:58,600  -->  00:01:01,780
best fit each set of points are the same.

18

00:01:01,780  -->  00:01:06,700
Even though this neighborhood has more expensive homes for the same square footage,

19

00:01:06,700  -->  00:01:09,120
this would be accounted for by the dummy variable,

20

00:01:09,120  -->  00:01:12,205
as this space between the two lines is consistent.

21

00:01:12,205  -->  00:01:14,020
Regardless of the neighborhood,

22

00:01:14,020  -->  00:01:19,535
the increase would be the exact same accounted for by this coefficient here in our model.

23

00:01:19,535  -->  00:01:24,570
However, imagine if the relationship actually looked like this for neighborhood B.

24

00:01:24,570  -->  00:01:28,990
Here, we can see that the slopes of these two lines no longer match.

25

00:01:28,990  -->  00:01:30,750
In order to account for this,

26

00:01:30,750  -->  00:01:33,190
we would want to add an interaction term between

27

00:01:33,190  -->  00:01:36,190
neighborhood and square footage to our model like this.

28

00:01:36,190  -->  00:01:39,670
Here, you can see that the way square footage is related to

29

00:01:39,670  -->  00:01:43,390
the home price is dependent on which neighborhood the home is in,

30

00:01:43,390  -->  00:01:48,990
or the way that x1 is related to y is dependent on the value of x2.

31

00:01:48,990  -->  00:01:51,670
The question of adding an interaction is a question

32

00:01:51,670  -->  00:01:54,390
about these slopes being close enough to equal.

33

00:01:54,390  -->  00:01:56,410
If the slopes are close to equal,

34

00:01:56,410  -->  00:01:58,350
then we don't add an interaction.

35

00:01:58,350  -->  00:02:01,150
However, if these slopes are not equal,

36

00:02:01,150  -->  00:02:05,470
this is an indication that we should add an interaction to our model.
